8:38 Please explain. If he's drinking all that beer, and the beer is like 97% water (355 ml of beer, 10mg of sodium chloride, right?) and that is higher than the 0.9% saline solution.... oh okay.... so the beer is roughly 3% sodium chloride and our bodies want 0.9% sodium chloride, so then the water leaves the cells in attempt to dilute the beer. Okay, cool.

I'm still confused because if tap water has the same concentration of sodium chloride, then how do we ever truly hydrate our bodies.

Sodium chloride is used elsewhere in the body as well and if drinking water doesn't hydrate us..... why is water leaving his cells when it should be flowing towards it?

snippet.textDisplay: Although it seems impossible,  I drank 15 to about 22 beers everyday for at least 25 years.  A ate just ‘ok,’ nothing too healthy nor unhealthy.  But rode a bike at least 12 miles a day and walked probably about >4 to 6 miles, on average.   I had some mild liver pain for about 10 years but always had good blood work.   I had a slightly enlarged liver and a small amount of Fatty Liver.   I stopped drinking now about 7 years ago only because it became a waste of money and I was basically never getting very drunk.   Knock wood but I am completely ‘unscathed.’  Kinda amazing!
